In interview you can say:

The main purpose of RAG is to avoid sending the entire document to the LLM. I first convert PDF chunks into embeddings and store them. When a user asks a question, I convert the query into an embedding and perform similarity search to retrieve the top-K most relevant chunks. Only those relevant chunks are sent to the LLM, which significantly reduces token usage, improves response speed, lowers inference cost, and reduces hallucinations.

Another interview question they may ask:

Why Top-K?
Suppose:

K = 1
Only one chunk is retrieved.

Sometimes information is spread across multiple chunks.

Example:

Chunk 10 → Class Definition

Chunk 11 → Inheritance

Chunk 12 → Polymorphism
If only one chunk is sent, context may be incomplete.

So we retrieve:

Top 3 or Top 5 chunks
to provide enough context while still keeping token usage low.

That's why your code uses:

retrieve_top_k(query, chunks, vectors, k=3)
This is a simple but real-world RAG architecture that many GenAI applications use before introducing vector databases like FAISS, Pinecone, or ChromaDB.


